### Chemical element with atomic number 26 (Fe)

Iron. Symbol Fe. Atomic number 26. It's a [metal](/Metal), part of the [first transition series](/First_transition_series), in [group 8](/Group_8_element). By mass, it’s the most common element on [Earth](/Earth), forming a significant chunk of the core. Fourth most abundant in the [Earth's crust](/Earth%27s_crust). Metallic iron? Mostly from [meteorites](/Meteorite).

To get usable metal from [iron ores](/Iron_ore), you need [kilns](/Kiln) or [furnaces](/Metallurgical_furnace) that can reach 1500 °C. That's 500 °C hotter than [smelting](/Smelting) [copper](/Copper). Humans figured this out in [Eurasia](/Eurasia) during the [2nd millennium BC](/2nd_millennium_BC). Then iron [tools](/Tool) and [weapons](/Weapon) started replacing [copper alloys](/List_of_copper_alloys) around 1200 BC. That’s when the [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age) ended and the [Iron Age](/Iron_Age) began.

Now, iron alloys like [steel](/Steel), [stainless steel](/Stainless_steel), [cast iron](/Cast_iron), and [special steels](/Alloy_steel) are the most common industrial metals. They’re strong and cheap. The [iron and steel industry](/Iron_and_steel_industry) is a big deal economically. Iron itself is the cheapest metal. A few dollars per kilogram. Hardly worth the effort.

Pure iron, when clean and shiny, is silvery-gray. It reacts with oxygen and [water](/Water) to form [rust](/Rust) – brown, black, hydrated [iron oxides](/Iron_oxide). Unlike other metal oxides, rust takes up more space, flakes off, and exposes more metal to… well, more rust. Its most common oxidation states are [iron(II)](/Iron(II)) and [iron(III)](/Iron(III)). It shares traits with other [transition metals](/Transition_metal), especially [ruthenium](/Ruthenium) and [osmium](/Osmium) in [group 8](/Group_8_element). Iron can exist in a wide range of [oxidation states](/Oxidation_state), from −4 to +7. It forms many [coordination complexes](/Coordination_complex) – [ferrocene](/Ferrocene), [ferrioxalate](/Potassium_ferrioxalate), [Prussian blue](/Prussian_blue) – some of which have actual uses.

An adult human body has about 4 grams of iron. Mostly in [hemoglobin](/Hemoglobin) and [myoglobin]. Essential for [oxygen transport](/Oxygen_transport) and storage. [Human iron metabolism](/Human_iron_metabolism) requires iron in the diet. It’s also key in [redox](/Redox) [enzymes](/Enzymes) for [cellular respiration](/Cellular_respiration) and [oxidation and reduction](/Oxidation_and_reduction) in plants and animals. &#91;10&#93;

### Characteristics

#### Allotropes

[Allotropes of iron](/Allotropes_of_iron) are just different arrangements of atoms in solid iron. At least four are known: [α](/Gamma), [γ](/Delta_(letter)), [δ](/Epsilon), and [ε](/Epsilon).

The first three are seen at normal pressures. Molten iron cools past 1538 °C and forms its δ allotrope with a [body-centered cubic](/Body-centered_cubic) (bcc) [crystal structure](/Crystal_structure). Below 1394 °C, it becomes γ-iron, [face-centered cubic](/Face-centered_cubic) (fcc) – also known as [austenite](/Austenite). At 912 °C and below, it reverts to the bcc α-iron. &#91;11&#93;

Under extreme pressure and high temperature – relevant for planetary cores – α-iron transforms into a [hexagonal close-packed](/Hexagonal_close-packed) (hcp) structure, known as [ε-iron](/Hexaferrum). This happens around 10 GPa and lower temperatures. &#91;12&#93;&#91;13&#93; The γ-phase also transforms to ε-iron under pressure. &#91;13&#93;

There’s some controversial evidence for a [β](/Beta) phase above 50 GPa and 1500 K, possibly [orthorhombic](/Orthorhombic) or double hcp. &#91;14&#93; (Confusingly, "β-iron" is also used for α-iron above its [Curie point](/Curie_temperature), when it becomes paramagnetic. &#91;11&#93;)

Earth's [inner core](/Earth%27s_inner_core) is thought to be an iron-[nickel](/Nickel) [alloy](/Alloy) with an ε (or β) structure. &#91;15&#93;

#### Melting and boiling points

[Phase diagram of pure iron at low pressure]

Iron's melting and boiling points, and its [enthalpy of atomization](/Enthalpy_of_atomization), are lower than earlier 3d elements like [scandium](/Scandium) to [chromium](/Chromium). This is because its 3d electrons are more tightly held. It’s higher than [manganese](/Manganese) because manganese has a half-filled 3d sub-shell, making its d-electrons less available for bonding. This trend repeats for [ruthenium](/Ruthenium) but not [osmium](/Osmium). &#91;16&#93;&#91;17&#93;

The melting point at pressures below 50 GPa is well-defined. Above that, data varies significantly. &#91;18&#93;

#### Magnetic properties

[Magnetization curves of ferromagnetic materials]

Below its [Curie point](/Curie_temperature) (770 °C), α-iron is [ferromagnetic](/Ferromagnetic). The spins of its two unpaired electrons align, creating a magnetic field. &#91;20&#93; This happens because these d-orbitals don't point directly at neighboring atoms, so they aren’t fully involved in metallic bonding. &#91;11&#93;

Without an external field, these spins form [magnetic domains](/Magnetic_domain), about 10 micrometers across. &#91;21&#93; Each domain has parallel spins, but the domains themselves can have different orientations, resulting in a net zero magnetic field.

Applying an external field causes favorable domains to grow. This property is crucial for [electrical transformers](/Electrical_transformer), [magnetic recording](/Magnetic_recording) heads, and [electric motors](/Electric_motor). Imperfections can "pin" these domains, making iron a permanent [magnet](/Magnet). &#91;20&#93;

Iron compounds like [ferrites](/Ferrite_(magnet)), including [magnetite](/Magnetite), exhibit similar behavior. Natural [lodestones](/Lodestone) were the first compasses. Magnetite particles were used in magnetic storage ( [core memories](/Computer_memory), [magnetic tapes](/Magnetic_tape)), but were replaced by [cobalt](/Cobalt)-based materials.

#### Isotopes

[Main isotopes of iron table]

Iron has four stable [isotopes](/Isotope): 54 Fe (5.845%), 56 Fe (91.754%), 57 Fe (2.119%), and 58 Fe (0.282%). Only 57 Fe has a [nuclear spin](/Nuclear_spin) (−1/2).

The nuclide 54 Fe might undergo [double electron capture](/Double_beta_decay), but it's never been observed. Its half-life is at least 4.4×10 20 years. &#91;22&#93;

60 Fe is an [extinct radionuclide](/Extinct_radionuclide) with a 2.6 million-year half-life. &#91;23&#93; It’s not found naturally on Earth, but its decay product is stable 60 Ni. &#91;9&#93; Studying 60 Fe in [meteorites](/Meteorite) has helped understand [nucleosynthesis](/Nucleosynthesis). Modern [mass spectrometry](/Mass_spectrometry) allows precise measurement of stable iron isotope ratios, with applications in Earth and [planetary science](/Planetary_science), and increasingly in biological and industrial fields. &#91;24&#93;

The correlation between 60 Ni and stable iron isotopes in meteorites like Semarkona and Chervony Kut suggests 60 Fe existed during the [Solar System's formation](/Formation_and_evolution_of_the_Solar_System). The energy from 60 Fe decay might have contributed to the [differentiation](/Planetary_differentiation) of asteroids. &#91;25&#93;

The most abundant isotope, 56 Fe, is significant because it's the endpoint of [nucleosynthesis](/Nucleosynthesis). &#91;26&#93; Fusion in [extremely massive stars](/Population_III_stars) produces 56 Ni, which decays through radioactive 56 Co to stable 56 Fe. &#91;27&#93;&#91;28&#93; This makes iron abundant in [red giants](/Red_giant), [iron meteorites](/Iron_meteorite), and planetary [cores](/Planetary_core). It’s the sixth most [abundant element](/Abundance_of_the_chemical_elements) in the [universe](/Universe) and the most common [refractory](/Refractory) element. &#91;29&#93;&#91;30&#93;&#91;31&#93;

Although 62 Ni has a slightly higher binding energy, stellar conditions favor iron production. &#91;32&#93; Elements heavier than iron are formed in [supernovae](/Supernova) via [rapid neutron capture](/R-process) on 56 Fe nuclei. &#91;29&#93;

In the far future, if protons don't decay, [fusion](/Nuclear_fusion) via [quantum tunnelling](/Quantum_tunnelling) could convert all matter into 56 Fe. &#91;33&#93;

### Origin and Occurrence in Nature

#### Cosmogenesis

Iron's abundance in [rocky planets](/Terrestrial_planet) is due to its production in type [Ia supernovae](/Type_Ia_supernova). &#91;34&#93;&#91;35&#93;

#### Metallic Iron

[Image of Widmanstatten pattern in an iron meteorite]

[Native iron](/Native_iron) is rare on Earth's surface due to oxidation. However, Earth's [inner](/Inner_core) and [outer core](/Outer_core) are believed to be largely iron alloys, possibly with [nickel](/Nickel). Electric currents in the outer core generate the [Earth's magnetic field](/Earth%27s_magnetic_field). Other [terrestrial planets](/Terrestrial_planet) and the [Moon](/Moon) likely have iron-alloy cores. [M-type asteroids](/M-type_asteroid) are also thought to be rich in metallic iron.

[Iron meteorites](/Iron_meteorite) are the primary source of natural metallic iron on Earth. Ancient artifacts have been found made from meteoritic iron before smelting was mastered. The [Inuit](/Inuit_people) used iron from the [Cape York meteorite](/Cape_York_meteorite) for tools. &#91;36&#93; About 1 in 20 [meteorites](/Meteorite) contain the iron-nickel minerals [taenite](/Taenite) and [kamacite](/Kamacite). &#91;37&#93; Native iron is also found in basalts that have interacted with carbon-rich rocks, reducing the oxygen [fugacity](/Fugacity) enough for iron to crystallize. This is called [telluric iron](/Telluric_iron) and is found in places like [Disko Island](/Disko_Island) in Greenland, [Yakutia](/Sakha_Republic) in [Russia](/Russia), and [Bühl](/B%C3%BChl_(Baden)) in [Germany](/Germany). &#91;38&#93;

#### Mantle Minerals

[Image of Ferropericlase]

[Ferropericlase](/Ferropericlase), a mix of MgO and FeO, makes up about 20% of Earth's [lower mantle](/Lower_mantle), making it the second most abundant mineral there. It's the main host for iron in this layer. &#91;39&#93; &#91;40&#93; [Silicate perovskite](/Silicate_perovskite), specifically the (Mg,Fe)SiO 3 form, is considered the most abundant [mineral](/Mineral) in Earth, making up 38% of its volume. &#91;41&#93;&#91;42&#93;

#### Earth's Crust

[Image of ochre path in Roussillon]

While iron is abundant on Earth, most of it is in the core. &#91;43&#93;&#91;44&#93; The [Earth's crust](/Crust_(geology)) has only about 5% iron, making it the fourth most abundant element there (after [oxygen](/Oxygen), [silicon](/Silicon), and [aluminium](/Aluminium)). &#91;45&#93;

Iron in the crust is mainly found in [iron minerals](/Iron_ore), such as [hematite](/Hematite) (Fe 2 O 3 ), [magnetite](/Magnetite) (Fe 3 O 4 ), and [siderite](/Siderite) (FeCO 3 ). Igneous rocks also contain [pyrrhotite](/Pyrrhotite) and [pentlandite](/Pentlandite). &#91;46&#93;&#91;47&#93; During [weathering](/Weathering), iron leaches out and oxidizes to [iron(III) oxide](/Iron(III)_oxide). &#91;48&#93;

[Image of Banded iron formation]

[Banded iron formations](/Banded_iron_formations), layers of iron oxides alternating with shale and chert, were laid down between 3,700 and 1,800 million years ago. &#91;49&#93;&#91;50&#93;

Iron(III) oxides, like [ochre](/Ochre), have been used as [pigments](/Pigment) since prehistory, contributing to the colors of rocks like the [Painted Hills](/Painted_Hills) in [Oregon](/Oregon) and the [Buntsandstein](/Buntsandstein). &#91;51&#93; Iron compounds give historical buildings their yellowish hue. &#91;53&#93; The red color of [Mars](/Mars_surface_color) is due to iron oxide-rich [regolith](/Regolith). &#91;54&#93;

Iron sulfide, [pyrite](/Pyrite) (FeS 2 ), contains iron but is difficult to extract. &#91;55&#93; Industrial production typically focuses on high-grade ores. &#91;56&#93;

The global stock of iron in use is 2,200 kg per capita. More developed countries have significantly more than less developed ones. &#91;57&#93;

#### Oceans

Iron plays a role in marine biota and climate. &#91;58&#93;

### Chemistry and Compounds

[Image of iron compounds table]

Iron exhibits the typical chemistry of [transition metals](/Transition_metal): variable oxidation states and extensive [coordination and organometallic chemistry](/Organometallic_chemistry). [Ferrocene](/Ferrocene), an iron compound, revolutionized [organometallic chemistry](/Organometallic_chemistry) in the 1950s. &#91;59&#93; Iron is considered a prototype transition metal due to its abundance and historical importance. &#91;60&#93; Its 26 electrons ([Ar]3d 6 4s 2 ) mean its outer electrons are close in energy and can be ionized. &#91;17&#93;

Iron primarily forms +2 ("ferrous") and +3 ("ferric") compounds. It also appears in higher oxidation states, like +6 in [potassium ferrate](/Potassium_ferrate) (K 2 FeO 4 ). &#91;61&#93; Iron(IV) is a common intermediate in biochemical reactions. &#91;62&#93;&#91;63&#93; Many [organoiron](/Organoiron_chemistry) compounds have formal oxidation states of +1, 0, −1, or even −2. [Mössbauer spectroscopy](/M%C3%B6ssbauer_spectroscopy) is used to assess oxidation states. &#91;64&#93; [Mixed valence compounds](/Mixed_valence_compound) like [magnetite](/Magnetite) and [Prussian blue](/Prussian_blue) contain both Fe(II) and Fe(III). &#91;63&#93; Prussian blue is the traditional "blue" in [blueprints](/Blueprint). &#91;65&#93;

Iron is the first transition metal that *cannot* reach its group oxidation state of +8. Ruthenium and osmium can, with osmium being more adept. &#91;11&#93; Iron shares similarities with [cobalt](/Cobalt) and [nickel](/Nickel) – the [iron triad](/Iron_triad) – which are also ferromagnetic at [room temperature](/Room_temperature). &#91;60&#93;

Unlike many metals, iron doesn't form amalgams with [mercury](/Mercury_(element)). This is why mercury is shipped in iron flasks. &#91;66&#93;

Iron is highly reactive, pyrophoric when finely divided, and dissolves easily in dilute acids to form Fe 2+ . It's passivated by concentrated [nitric acid](/Nitric_acid) due to an oxide layer, but reacts with [hydrochloric acid](/Hydrochloric_acid). &#91;11&#93; High-purity [electrolytic iron](/Electrolytic_iron) is resistant to rust.

#### Binary Compounds

##### Oxides and Sulfides

[Image of hydrated iron(III) chloride]

Common oxides include [iron(II,III) oxide](/Iron(II,III)_oxide) (Fe 3 O 4 ) and [iron(III) oxide](/Iron(III)_oxide) (Fe 2 O 3 ). [Iron(II) oxide](/Iron(II)_oxide) (FeO) is unstable at room temperature. These are the main [ores of iron](/Iron_ore). They're used in [ferrites](/Ferrite_(magnet)) and pigments. [Iron pyrite](/Iron_pyrite) (FeS 2 ), or "fool's gold," is a common sulfide, but not an iron(IV) compound; it's an iron(II) [polysulfide](/Polysulfide). &#91;63&#93;&#91;67&#93;

[Pourbaix diagram of iron]

##### Halides

Ferrous and ferric halides are well-known. Ferrous halides are formed by reacting iron metal with [hydrohalic acid](/Hydrohalic_acid). &#91;63&#93;

Fe + 2 HX → FeX 2 + H 2 (X = F, Cl, Br, I)

Iron reacts with fluorine, chlorine, and bromine to form ferric halides, with [ferric chloride](/Ferric_chloride) being the most common. &#91;68&#93;

2 Fe + 3 X 2 → 2 FeX 3 (X = F, Cl, Br)

[Ferric iodide](/Ferric_iodide) is unstable, as Fe 3+ is oxidizing and I − is reducing. &#91;68&#93;

2 I − + 2 Fe 3+ → I 2 + 2 Fe 2+ (E 0 = +0.23 V)

Ferric iodide can be prepared under specific conditions, but complexes with soft bases are more stable. &#91;69&#93;&#91;70&#93;

#### Solution Chemistry

[Image comparing colors of ferrate and permanganate solutions]

Standard reduction potentials in acidic solution: &#91;11&#93;

[Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 2+ + 2 e − ⇌ Fe E 0 = −0.447 V
[Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ + e − ⇌ [Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 2+ E 0 = +0.77 V
FeO 2− 4 + 8 H 3 O + + 3 e − ⇌ [Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ + 6 H 2 O E 0 = +2.20 V

The tetrahedral [ferrate(VI)](/Ferrate) anion is a strong oxidizer. &#91;68&#93;

4 FeO 2− 4 + 34 H 2 O → 4 [Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ + 20 OH − + 3 O 2

The pale-violet [aquo complex](/Aquo_complex) [Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ is acidic. &#91;71&#93;

[Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ ⇌ [Fe(H 2 O) 5 (OH)] 2+ + H + [K](/Equilibrium_constant) = 10 −3.05 mol dm −3
[Fe(H 2 O) 5 (OH)] 2+ ⇌ [Fe(H 2 O) 4 (OH) 2 ] + + H + K = 10 −3.26 mol dm −3
2[Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 3+ ⇌ [Fe(H 2 O) 4 (OH)]4+2 + 2H + + 2H 2 O K = 10 −2.91 mol dm −3

As pH rises, hydrolyzed species form, and above pH 2–3, reddish-brown hydrous [iron(III) oxide](/Iron(III)_oxide) precipitates. &#91;71&#93; The pale green iron(II) hexaquo ion [Fe(H 2 O) 6 ] 2+ doesn't hydrolyze much. Carbonate precipitation forms white [iron(II) carbonate](/Iron(II)_carbonate), which oxidizes in air to [iron(III) oxide](/Iron(III)_oxide). &#91;72&#93;

#### Coordination Compounds

[Image of ferrioxalate enantiomorphs]

Iron has extensive coordination and organometallic chemistry. The ferrioxalate ion shows [helical chirality](/Helical_chirality). &#91;71&#93; [Potassium ferrioxalate](/Potassium_ferrioxalate) is used in [actinometry](/Actinometry). &#91;77&#93;

[Image of crystal structure of iron(II) oxalate dihydrate]

Iron(III) complexes are similar to [chromium(III)](/Chromium) complexes but prefer O-donor ligands. They often have intense colors. The [ferric chloride test](/Ferric_chloride_test) detects phenols. &#91;71&#93;

3 ArOH + FeCl 3 → Fe(OAr) 3 + 3 HCl (Ar = [aryl](/Aryl))

Fluoro complexes of iron(III) are most stable. Chloro complexes favor tetrahedral coordination, like [FeCl 4 ] − . [Thiocyanate](/Thiocyanate) forms blood-red [Fe(SCN)(H 2 O) 5 ] 2+ , a test for iron(III). &#91;71&#93; Most iron(III) complexes are high-spin, except those with ligands high in the [spectrochemical series](/Spectrochemical_series), like [cyanide](/Cyanide). [Fe(CN) 6 ] 3− is low-spin. Iron exhibits all possible [spin states](/Spin_states_(d_electrons)) for d-block elements, from 0 to 5/2. &#91;67&#93;

Iron(II) complexes are less stable but prefer O-donor ligands less. &#91;72&#93;

#### Organometallic Compounds

[Image of iron pentacarbonyl]

[Organoiron chemistry](/Organoiron_chemistry) studies iron compounds with covalent carbon bonds. These include [cyanide complexes](/Cyanometallate), [carbonyl complexes](/Carbonyl_complex), and [sandwich compounds](/Sandwich_compound).

[Image of Prussian blue]

[Prussian blue](/Prussian_blue), or ferric ferrocyanide, is an old pigment. &#91;63&#93; [Iron pentacarbonyl](/Iron_pentacarbonyl), Fe(CO) 5, yields [carbonyl iron](/Carbonyl_iron) powder. &#91;78&#93;

[Image of ferrocene structure and powder]

[Ferrocene](/Ferrocene), discovered in 1951, is a remarkably stable [sandwich compound](/Sandwich_compound). &#91;79&#93;&#91;80&#93;&#91;81&#93;&#91;82&#93; It remains a key model in the field. &#91;83&#93;

Iron catalysts are used in reactions like [transfer hydrogenation](/Transfer_hydrogenation). &#91;84&#93;

### Industrial Uses

#### As Structural Material

Iron is the most used metal, over 90% of world production. &#91;129&#93; It's strong and cheap, used in machinery, [rails](/Track_(rail_transport)), [automobiles](/Automobile), [ship hulls](/Hull_(watercraft)), [rebar](/Rebar), and buildings. Pure iron is soft, so it's usually alloyed into steel. &#91;130&#93;

#### Mechanical Properties

[Table of tensile strength and Brinell hardness of iron forms]

Mechanical properties are critical. Pure iron is soft, even softer than aluminum in single-crystal form. &#91;127&#93; Industrial pure iron has a hardness of 20–30 Brinell. &#91;132&#93;

Carbon content significantly increases hardness and strength. &#91;133&#93; Iron is easier to work than [ruthenium](/Ruthenium) or [osmium](/Osmium). &#91;17&#93;

#### Types of Steels and Alloys

[Iron-carbon phase diagram]

α-Iron dissolves little carbon (0.021% max at 910 °C). &#91;134&#93; Austenite (γ-iron) dissolves more (2.04% max at 1146 °C) and is used in [stainless steel](/Stainless_steel). &#91;21&#93;

Iron is classified by purity and additives. [Pig iron] has high carbon (3.5–4.5%) and contaminants. It's an intermediate for cast iron and steel. &#91;135&#93;

"White" cast irons have carbon as cementite (Fe 3 C), making them hard and brittle. &#91;17&#93; Slow cooling of iron with 0.8% carbon yields [pearlite](/Pearlite) (layers of cementite and α-iron). Rapid cooling creates hard, brittle [martensite](/Martensite). &#91;17&#93;

[Gray iron] has carbon as graphite flakes, creating stress concentration points. [Ductile iron] has graphite as spheroids, making it tougher. &#91;136&#93;

[Wrought iron] has low carbon (<0.25%) and slag, giving it a fibrous texture. It's more corrosion-resistant than steel but largely replaced by [mild steel](/Mild_steel). [Carbon steel] has ≤2% carbon. &#91;137&#93; [Alloy steels](/Alloy_steel) contain other metals, raising costs for specialized uses. [Stainless steel](/Stainless_steel) is common. High-strength, low-alloy (HSLA) steels offer good properties at low cost. &#91;137&#93;&#91;138&#93;&#91;139&#93;

High-purity iron alloys have enhanced properties like [ductility](/Ductility), [tensile strength](/Tensile_strength), and corrosion resistance.

Iron is also used for radiation shielding, being stronger than [lead](/Lead) mechanically. &#91;140&#93;

Rusting is a major drawback, costing over 1% of the world economy. &#91;141&#93; Protection methods include painting, [galvanization](/Galvanization), and [passivation](/Passivation_(chemistry)). Rusting mechanism:
Cathode: 3 O 2 + 6 H 2 O + 12 e − → 12 OH −
Anode: 4 Fe → 4 Fe 2+ + 8 e − ; 4 Fe 2+ → 4 Fe 3+ + 4 e −
Overall: 4 Fe + 3 O 2 + 6 H 2 O → 4 Fe(OH) 3 or 4 FeO(OH) + 4 H 2 O
The electrolyte is often [iron(II) sulfate](/Iron(II)_sulfate) or salt particles. &#91;141&#93;

#### Catalysts and Reagents

Iron is inexpensive and non-toxic, leading to research in Fe-based catalysts. &#91;142&#93; It's less common as a commercial catalyst than other metals, but pervasive in biological enzymes. &#91;143&#93;

Iron catalysts are used in the [Haber–Bosch process](/Haber%E2%80%93Bosch_process) and [Fischer–Tropsch process](/Fischer%E2%80%93Tropsch_process). &#91;144&#93; Powdered iron is used in the [Bechamp reduction](/Bechamp_reduction) of [nitrobenzene](/Nitrobenzene) to [aniline](/Aniline). &#91;145&#93;

#### Iron Compounds

[Iron(III) oxide](/Iron(III)_oxide) with [aluminium](/Aluminium) powder creates the [thermite reaction](/Thermite_reaction), used for welding and ore purification. Iron oxides are used as [pigments](/Pigment).

[Iron(III) chloride](/Iron(III)_chloride) is used in water purification, dyeing, animal feed, and as an [etchant](/Industrial_etching) for [copper](/Copper) in [printed circuit boards](/Printed_circuit_board). &#91;146&#93;

[Iron(II) sulfate](/Iron(II)_sulfate) is a precursor to other iron compounds and used to fortify foods and treat [iron deficiency anemia](/Iron_deficiency_anemia). &#91;146&#93;

[Sodium nitroprusside](/Sodium_nitroprusside), a [vasodilator](/Vasodilator), is on the [World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines](/WHO_Model_List_of_Essential_Medicines). &#91;148&#93;

### Biological and Pathological Role

Iron is essential for life. &#91;10&#93;&#91;149&#93;&#91;150&#93; [Iron–sulfur clusters](/Iron%E2%80%93sulfur_cluster) are vital in enzymes like [nitrogenase](/Nitrogenase). Iron proteins handle oxygen transport and [electron transfer](/Electron_transfer). &#91;151&#93;

[Heme B structure]

In humans, examples include hemoglobin, [cytochrome](/Cytochrome), and [catalase](/Catalase). &#91;10&#93;&#91;152&#93; An adult has about 4 grams of iron, mostly in hemoglobin. The body recycles hemoglobin iron. &#91;151&#93;&#91;153&#93;

Microbial growth can be affected by iron oxidation/reduction. &#91;154&#93;

#### Biochemistry

Iron acquisition is challenging because ferric iron is poorly soluble. Organisms use [siderophores](/Siderophore) to bind and transport iron. &#91;155&#93;&#91;156&#93;&#91;157&#93;

In humans, [transferrin](/Transferrin) binds and transports iron from the [duodenum](/Duodenum) to cells. &#91;10&#93;&#91;159&#93; Transferrin's high stability constant ensures efficient iron uptake. In bone marrow, transferrin is reduced, and iron is stored as [ferritin](/Ferritin) for hemoglobin synthesis. &#91;151&#93;

[Heme proteins](/Heme_proteins) like hemoglobin and myoglobin are key iron compounds. They transport gases, form [enzymes](/Enzymes), and transfer [electrons](/Electron). &#91;151&#93; [Metalloproteins](/Metalloproteins) like ferritin and [rubredoxin](/Rubredoxin) also contain iron. &#91;151&#93; Enzymes like [catalase](/Catalase), &#91;160&#93; [lipoxygenases](/Lipoxygenases), &#91;161&#93; and [IRE-BP](/IRE-BP) are vital. &#91;162&#93;

Hemoglobin carries oxygen from lungs to muscles, where it's transferred to myoglobin for storage. &#91;10&#93; Hemoglobin transports CO 2 back to the lungs. &#91;151&#93; In hemoglobin, iron is in a heme group. Its coordination sites bind oxygen reversibly. &#91;151&#93; When oxygen-free (deoxyhemoglobin), Fe 2+ is high-spin, and the heme group bends. &#91;151&#93;

Oxygen binding causes Fe 2+ to switch to low-spin, shrinking the ion and flattening the heme group. This binding also triggers cooperative changes in hemoglobin's subunits, increasing oxygen affinity. Myoglobin lacks this effect. The [Bohr effect](/Bohr_effect) describes how CO 2 reduces hemoglobin's oxygen affinity. &#91;151&#93;

[Carboxyhemoglobin structure]

Carbon monoxide and [phosphorus trifluoride](/Phosphorus_trifluoride) are toxic because they bind hemoglobin more strongly than oxygen. Cyanide mainly interferes with [cytochrome a](/Cytochrome_a). &#91;151&#93; Cytochromes use heme groups for glucose metabolism. Electron transfer occurs as iron cycles between +2 and +3 states. &#91;151&#93;

[Iron–sulfur proteins](/Iron%E2%80%93sulfur_protein) are crucial for electron transfer, as iron can exist in +2 and +3 states. They contain multiple iron atoms coordinated to sulfur. [Rubredoxin](/Rubredoxin) is the simplest. [Ferredoxins](/Ferredoxin) have multiple iron atoms. &#91;151&#93;

Mussels use iron-based bonds in their [cuticles](/Cuticle) for grip. &#91;164&#93;

#### Nutrition

**Diet**
Rich sources of iron include [red meat](/Red_meat), [oysters](/Oyster), [beans](/Bean), [poultry](/Poultry), [fish](/Fish), [leaf vegetables](/Leaf_vegetable), [tofu](/Tofu), and [blackstrap molasses](/Blackstrap_molasses). &#91;10&#93; Foods like [bread](/Bread) and [breakfast cereals](/Breakfast_cereal) are often fortified. &#91;10&#93;&#91;165&#93;

Dietary supplements often use [iron(II) fumarate](/Iron(II)_fumarate), though [iron(II) sulfate](/Iron(II)_sulfate) is cheaper and equally absorbed. &#91;146&#93; Elemental iron is also used. Iron is best absorbed when chelated to amino acids, like [glycine](/Glycine). &#91;167&#93;&#91;168&#93;

**Dietary Recommendations**
RDAs vary by age and sex. For women aged 19-50, it's 18 mg/day. Pregnancy: 27 mg/day. &#91;10&#93; ULs (Tolerable upper intake levels) are set to prevent toxicity. &#91;169&#93; European recommendations (PRIs) are similar but slightly higher. &#91;170&#93;

Infants on cow's milk may need supplements. Frequent blood donors should monitor iron levels. &#91;173&#93;

For U.S. labeling, 100% DV is 18 mg. &#91;174&#93;&#91;175&#93;

#### Deficiency

[Iron deficiency] is the most common nutritional deficiency globally. &#91;10&#93;&#91;176&#93;&#91;177&#93;&#91;178&#93; Untreated deficiency leads to [iron-deficiency anemia](/Iron-deficiency_anemia). Children and pre-menopausal women are most susceptible. Severe cases can cause heart problems, pregnancy complications, and developmental delays. &#91;180&#93;

The brain is somewhat protected from acute deficiency. &#91;181&#93; Prolonged deficiency may reduce brain iron, impacting neurotransmitter synthesis and myelin. &#91;184&#93; Animal studies show changes resembling Parkinson's and Huntington's. &#91;185&#93;&#91;186&#93; However, iron accumulation in the brain is also linked to Parkinson's. &#91;187&#93;

#### Excess

[Iron overload] occurs when the body can't regulate iron uptake properly, often due to genetic defects affecting [hepcidin](/Hepcidin). &#91;189&#93; This can lead to [hemochromatosis](/Hemochromatosis). &#91;10&#93; People should not take iron supplements without medical advice. &#91;190&#93;

Excess iron creates reactive [free radicals](/Free_radical), damaging cells. Toxicity occurs when iron exceeds transferrin's binding capacity. Organs like the [heart](/Heart) and [liver](/Liver) can be damaged. &#91;191&#93; Lethal dose is around 60 mg/kg. &#91;192&#93; Iron poisoning is a common cause of death in young children. &#91;192&#93; DRI sets the UL at 45 mg/day for adults. &#91;193&#93;

Deferoxamine is a chelating agent used to treat iron toxicity. &#91;194&#93;&#91;195&#93;

#### ADHD

Some research links low [thalamic](/Thalamus) iron to [ADHD](/Attention_deficit_hyperactivity_disorder). &#91;196&#93; Iron supplementation may help, especially the inattentive subtype. &#91;197&#93; A 2012 study found no correlation between serum ferritin and ADHD. &#91;198&#93;

#### Cancer

Iron's role in cancer is complex. Chemotherapy can cause iron deficiency, treated with IV iron. &#91;200&#93; Iron overload, possibly from red meat consumption, may promote [tumor](/Tumor) growth and cancer susceptibility, particularly [colorectal cancer](/Colorectal_cancer). &#91;10&#93;&#91;200&#93;

#### Marine Systems

Iron is a limiting nutrient for plankton in oceans. &#91;201&#93; Too little iron can slow phytoplankton growth. &#91;202&#93; Iron can enter oceans via rivers and the atmosphere. &#91;204&#93; Sea ice in the Arctic stores and releases iron. &#91;205&#93; The iron cycle fluctuates between aqueous and particle forms. &#91;206&#93;

